Simulating DQIs: worked example



victim_divide &lt;- function(base_y1, base_y2){
  ((base_y2 - 1) - (base_y1 - 1)) / (base_y1 - 1)
}


This is what the Victimization Divide formula looks like in R

How much has victimization inequality changed?



draws_2015 &lt;-
  draws_2015 |&gt;
  as.data.frame() |&gt;
  as_tibble() |&gt;
  mutate(est = exp(`fct_rev(sex)men`))

draws_2020 &lt;-
  draws_2020 |&gt;
  as.data.frame() |&gt;
  as_tibble() |&gt;
  mutate(est = exp(`fct_rev(sex)men`))

# combine the results
sim_dat &lt;-
  tibble(
    vd = victim_divide(base_y1 = draws_2015$est,
                       base_y2 = draws_2020$est)
  )


Once we tidy the results up a bit, we can pass these simulated draws to our victim_divide() function to get a distribution of Victimization Divides.
From these we can calculate confidence intervals to see how sure we can be that victimization inequality between men and women fell by 52%.

Calculating predictions



library(ggplot2)

data.frame(
  simd = seq(1, 6976)
) |&gt; 
  mutate(pred_vio = exp(2.4573632 + simd * -0.0003029)) |&gt; 
  ggplot(aes(x = simd, y = pred_vio)) +
  geom_line()









In fact, we can calculate these predictions across the whole range of SIMD.
This gives a much more useful summary of the results compared to just the model coefficients.

Calculating predictions



library(ggplot2)

data.frame(
  simd = seq(1, 6976)
) |&gt; 
  mutate(pred_vio = exp(2.4573632 + simd * -0.0003029)) |&gt; 
  ggplot(aes(x = simd, y = pred_vio)) +
  geom_line()









When we visualized the results from this model before we only got a point estimate for the expected number of violent crimes at each level of SIMD.
This doesn‚Äôt express the uncertainty in these results as described by the model‚Äôs standard errors.
